+## `toRegExp(pattern: string, options?: ToRegExpOptions) => RegExp`
+
+Convert a glob pattern to a JavaScript `RegExp` object.
+
+By default, the generated `RegExp` is not anchored to the start of the string (`^`),
+so it matches the relative path as a suffix of an absolute path, consistent with
+the standard `glob` behavior. To anchor the `RegExp` to the start of the string
+and match the full path, set the `fullMatch: true` option.
+
+Options:
+- `fullMatch`: Set to `true` to keep the `^` anchor, meaning the `RegExp` will only match the entire string.
+- All other `GlobOptions` (like `nocase`, `windowsPathsNoEscape`) are supported.
+
+```js
+const { glob } = require('glob')
+
+// use with Array.filter
+const paths = ['/root/foo.js', '/root/bar.json', '/root/baz.js']
+const jsFiles = paths.filter(p => glob.toRegExp('*.js').test(p))
+console.log(jsFiles) // ['/root/foo.js', '/root/baz.js']
+
+// match full strings
+const isFoo = glob.toRegExp('foo/*.js', { fullMatch: true })
+isFoo.test('foo/bar.js') // true
+isFoo.test('a/foo/bar.js') // false
+
+// Use with sed or other command line tools
+const sedCommand = `sed -E 's/${glob.toRegExp('*.js').source}/.ts/g' file.txt`
+```
+
+## `escapeRegExp(str: string) => string`
+
+Escape regular expression special characters in a string.
+
+Unlike `escape`, which escapes glob special characters, this function escapes characters
+that have special meaning in JavaScript's `RegExp` engine.
+
+```js
+const { glob } = require('glob')
+const escaped = glob.escapeRegExp('*.js') // '\\*\\.js'
+```
+
 ## Class `Glob`
 
 An object that can perform glob pattern traversals.
